---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';

const path = '/compare/omnisend-vs-yotpo-email-sms';
const title = 'Omnisend vs Yotpo Email & SMS: Shopify Email Tools Compared';
const desc = 'Omnisend vs Yotpo Email & SMS for Shopify email tools — standalone multichannel journeys vs reviews-loyalty bundling, push recovery, post-purchase trust loops, and renewal math.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'When should a Shopify store choose Omnisend over Yotpo Email & SMS?',
    answer: 'Pick Omnisend when you want email, SMS, and web push in one journey builder without adopting Yotpo Reviews or Loyalty. It ships welcome, cart, and post-purchase flows fast for merchants who treat retention as a messaging problem first. Yotpo Email & SMS makes more sense when review velocity, loyalty points, and UGC already drive repeat revenue and you want those signals inside the same automation canvas.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Yotpo Email & SMS require Yotpo Reviews to be worth it?',
    answer: 'Not technically, but economically it usually does. Without Reviews or Loyalty live, you pay suite complexity for integrations you are not using. A pottery studio sending kiln-care education and restock alerts gets more from Omnisend\'s presets unless they also run a points program tied to glaze refills. Evaluate bundle renewal as a whole contract, not email line item alone.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Omnisend web push compare to Yotpo\'s channel mix?',
    answer: 'Omnisend includes web push as a first-class step in automations — useful for board game stores when mobile browsers abandon pre-order carts without opting into SMS. Yotpo Email & SMS focuses on email and text tied to reviews and loyalty triggers. If push is part of your recovery stack, Omnisend has a structural advantage Yotpo does not replicate natively.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which platform handles artisan coffee replenishment better?',
    answer: 'Omnisend handles consumption-based replenishment with straightforward delay logic and SMS nudges at day 21. Yotpo adds loyalty earn reminders and review prompts in the same post-purchase window — powerful if subscribers redeem points on bean refills, noisy if you only need a simple reorder email. Coffee merchants without loyalty should default Omnisend; subscription-plus-points programs lean Yotpo.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What does pricing look like at 12,000 contacts with moderate SMS?',
    answer: 'Omnisend Standard or Pro at 12k contacts typically lands $100–180/mo before SMS credits. Yotpo Email & SMS pricing often appears inside a broader Yotpo agreement — attractive when Reviews and Loyalty are bundled, opaque when you only wanted email. Model 12 months of SMS separately; Yotpo renewal conversations frequently surface the true automation cost.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Omnisend and Yotpo coexist on one Shopify store?',
    answer: 'Technically yes, practically painful. Duplicate cart recovery, conflicting suppression, and split revenue attribution are the failure modes. If Yotpo Reviews stays for UGC but Omnisend owns lifecycle, disable Yotpo cart and welcome flows explicitly. One platform should own orchestration; the other should feed events or capture reviews only.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which tool is faster to go live for a climbing gear catalog?',
    answer: 'Omnisend — prebuilt ecommerce automations with push at step two cover browse-heavy categories where shoppers research harness fit across multiple PDPs. Yotpo shines after the first purchase when review photos of gear in use and loyalty credits on carabiner bundles matter. For pre-first-order retention, Omnisend wins on time-to-live.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What buyer workflow should settle Omnisend vs Yotpo?',
    answer: 'Draft five jobs: welcome by signup source, cart at 60 minutes with inventory check, post-purchase education excluding gifts, review request at day 10, winback at 90 days. Score build time, whether loyalty or review steps are load-bearing, and whether push belongs in the journey. If review and points KPIs are central, Yotpo. If multichannel speed and vendor independence matter, Omnisend.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Omnisend vs Yotpo Email & SMS</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="catalog-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Omnisend vs Yotpo Email & SMS for Shopify email tools</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Two multichannel answers to Shopify retention — one built to stand alone, one built to complete a reviews-and-loyalty stack. We evaluated both against a $68k/mo artisan coffee roaster already running Yotpo Reviews, a climbing gear shop with no UGC program and heavy mobile browse, and a board game store where pre-order hype and loyalty redemption share the same post-purchase window. The question is not which sends more email; it is which catalog of newsletters, lifecycle automation, and transactional-style customer moments matches how your store actually earns repeat revenue.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Standalone multichannel', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Email, SMS, and push in one journey without suite lock-in.' },
            { label: 'Reviews + loyalty loops', tool: 'Yotpo Email & SMS', reason: 'Post-purchase UGC and points wired into the same retention canvas.' },
            { label: 'Time to first flows', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Prebuilt welcome, cart, and post-purchase presets ship in days.' },
            { label: 'Trust-driven repeat', tool: 'Yotpo Email & SMS', reason: 'Review prompts and earn reminders when social proof moves revenue.' },
            { label: 'Web push recovery', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Native push steps for mobile browse without SMS spend.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Omnisend</th><th>Yotpo Email & SMS</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Catalog fit</td><td>Multichannel ecommerce automation</td><td>Retention suite extension for Reviews/Loyalty</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Free tier; paid scales by contacts</td><td>Module-based; often bundled with Yotpo stack</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Newsletters</td><td>Campaign editor with product blocks</td><td>Campaigns plus loyalty-aware segments</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Lifecycle depth</td><td>Visual workflows, push at step two</td><td>Review and points triggers as journey anchors</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Transactional-style</td><td>Order and fulfillment-triggered messages</td><td>Shipment plus review request sequencing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SMS</td><td>Native in journeys</td><td>Native, tied to loyalty and campaigns</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Push</td><td>Web push included</td><td>Not a core channel</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Best when</td><td>No Yotpo footprint; speed matters</td><td>Reviews or Loyalty already live</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>What this comparison is actually about</h2>
        <p>
          Omnisend and Yotpo Email & SMS sit in the same Shopify email-tools category — newsletters, lifecycle automation, and transactional-style customer moments — but they punish different operational mistakes. Omnisend is optimized when you need cart, welcome, and post-purchase live in days. Yotpo Email & SMS is optimized when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Buyers who choose on brand recognition alone often end up paying for depth they never open or speed they outgrow in ninety days.
        </p>
        <p>
          We tested both against specialty catalogs where retention is genuinely hard: vinyl scarcity, keyboard group buys, tea replenishment, climbing research cycles, pottery gifts, outdoor segmentation, board game allocation, coffee roast dates, and camping quiz capture. Those verticals stress education, suppression, and timing more honestly than generic one-size-fits-all demos. The writeup below is intentionally merchant-specific — not a feature matrix dressed in adjectives.
        </p>
        <h2>Pottery Studio ($31k/mo) — exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging</h2>
        <p>
          The pottery studio does 480 orders/mo at roughly $31k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows class waitlists and glaze-kit starter sets, which means email must handle kiln-care post-purchase and holiday gift exclusions before holiday starter-set rush — not after support tickets spike. Omnisend contributes prebuilt multichannel journeys with email, SMS, and push; Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Yotpo Email & SMS reduced preview-time surprises because reviews. Omnisend remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          High-AOV safety content beats coupons. Climbing shoppers wanted retirement timelines and certification context; a 10% off rope email on day two would have trained worst practices. Education-first sequencing recovered more margin than blanket promos. For pottery studio specifically, exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday starter-set rush becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Record Store Day: vinyl record shop retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The vinyl record shop does 1,800 orders/mo at roughly $72k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows limited pressings with 200–400 unit runs, which means email must handle VIP drop allocation and grading education before promos before Record Store Day — not after support tickets spike. Omnisend contributes prebuilt multichannel journeys with email, SMS, and push; Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Omnisend reduced preview-time surprises because prebuilt multichannel journeys with email. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          High-AOV safety content beats coupons. Climbing shoppers wanted retirement timelines and certification context; a 10% off rope email on day two would have trained worst practices. Education-first sequencing recovered more margin than blanket promos. For vinyl record shop specifically, suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Record Store Day becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Outdoor Gear Retailer: layering guides and ultralight segment tags</h2>
        <p>
          The outdoor gear retailer does 2,400 orders/mo at roughly $112k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows layering guides and ultralight segment tags, which means email must handle Memorial Day tent promos only after education sends before Memorial Day sale week — not after support tickets spike. Omnisend contributes prebuilt multichannel journeys with email, SMS, and push; Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Yotpo Email & SMS reduced preview-time surprises because reviews. Omnisend remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Allocation fear creates support tickets, not only unsubscribes. Board game pre-orders needed clear fulfillment-state emails; ambiguous cart recovery during allocation windows duplicated support load. State-aware automation paid for itself in Zendesk hours. For outdoor gear retailer specifically, merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day sale week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>How mechanical keyboard vendor emails through GB close deadlines</h2>
        <p>
          The mechanical keyboard vendor does 940 orders/mo at roughly $58k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows six-week group-buy cycles on $180–$420 kits, which means email must handle GB close suppression and switch-type education across five PDPs before GB close deadlines — not after support tickets spike. Omnisend contributes prebuilt multichannel journeys with email, SMS, and push; Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Omnisend reduced preview-time surprises because prebuilt multichannel journeys with email. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Gift confusion is a December tax. Tea gift boxes and pottery starter sets both saw recipients hit unsubscribe when reorder emails assumed they were loyal drinkers or makers. Order property filters are not optional — they are deliverability insurance. For mechanical keyboard vendor specifically, halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise GB close deadlines becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Board Game Store ($67k/mo) — pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders</h2>
        <p>
          The board game store does 1,050 orders/mo at roughly $67k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows pre-order allocation anxiety on hot titles, which means email must handle pre-order state machines and fulfillment pivots after allocation closes before Essen release week — not after support tickets spike. Omnisend contributes prebuilt multichannel journeys with email, SMS, and push; Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Omnisend reduced preview-time surprises because prebuilt multichannel journeys with email. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Allocation fear creates support tickets, not only unsubscribes. Board game pre-orders needed clear fulfillment-state emails; ambiguous cart recovery during allocation windows duplicated support load. State-aware automation paid for itself in Zendesk hours. For board game store specifically, pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Essen release week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Q4 gift-box peak: specialty tea merchant retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The specialty tea merchant does 720 orders/mo at roughly $44k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows 28–35 day tin replenishment with gift-box seasonality, which means email must handle subscription skip handling and gift-buyer exclusions in December before Q4 gift-box peak — not after support tickets spike. Omnisend contributes prebuilt multichannel journeys with email, SMS, and push; Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Omnisend reduced preview-time surprises because prebuilt multichannel journeys with email. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Inventory truth mattered as much as copy. When a limited run sold out mid-send, the tool that pulled live variant availability prevented angry clicks — the vinyl shop learned that on a 300-unit pressing that died during a two-hour send window. For specialty tea merchant specifically, split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Q4 gift-box peak becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Yotpo Email & SMS workflow reality: strengths, friction, and billing</h2>
        <p>
          Omnisend shines when you need cart, welcome, and post-purchase live in days. Its friction shows when custom GB or preorder state machines dominate revenue. Yotpo Email & SMS shines when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Its friction shows when you only need email without UGC or points. Merchants that ignore friction points buy the wrong ceiling — or the wrong floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          Billing amplifies behavior. Omnisend (contacts plus message volume) rewards send discipline or punishes broadcast volume depending on your calendar. Yotpo Email & SMS (modular plans by product) does the opposite in many stores. The vinyl shop imported thousands of waitlist emails while orders stayed flat; profile-style billing hurt. The outdoor retailer blasted engaged segments every May; send-weighted billing hurt. Model your real year, not a calm month.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reporting expectations differ. If your team opens lifecycle revenue reports every Monday, buy the tool that makes those reports trustworthy out of the box. If nobody reviews reports, buy for time-to-live and edit safety — not predictive metrics that become dashboard wallpaper.
        </p>
        <h2>Newsletter layer: editorial merchandising without discount training</h2>
        <p>
          Newsletters still matter. Coffee origin stories, vinyl staff picks, keyboard switch explainers, and climbing trip reports build trust before product blocks. Omnisend and Yotpo Email & SMS both send product campaigns; the operational difference is how often you change hero SKUs mid-week and how live inventory syncs when a limited run sells out.
        </p>
        <p>
          Training customers to wait for codes is a hidden churn driver. If every Thursday email is twenty percent off, replenishment and winback lose meaning. Use editorial sends to teach grading, certification, player count, roast profiles, and tent capacity — then merchandise. Discipline beats platform.
        </p>
        <h2>Transactional-style moments and promo collision</h2>
        <p>
          Password resets belong on transactional infrastructure. Shipment delays, preorder timeline changes, and subscription skip confirmations can live in marketing ESPs only if copy and domain strategy separate operational tone from promos. Coffee brands on shared domains see complaint spikes when a roast release email resembles a receipt.
        </p>
        <p>
          Post-purchase cross-sells are where brands blur lines. An order update with three discount blocks reads promotional to filters when volume spikes. Document message categories before peak season. See <a class="link" href="/guides/deliverability">deliverability guide</a> for domain and reputation splitting.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing models that punish different mistakes</h2>
        <p>
          At 12,000–18,000 contacts, plans converge until they do not. Sunset cold imports before quoting either tool. Add SMS, push, reviews, or loyalty modules to the same spreadsheet — modular suites like Yotpo Email & SMS punish partial adoption.
        </p>
        <p>
          Project November, not February. Record Store Day, GB closes, Essen week, Memorial Day, and holiday gift-box peaks change send volume and support load. <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">Pricing models</a> helps build the year view.
        </p>
        <h2>Implementation workload and team shape</h2>
        <p>
          Integration is the easy hour. Exclusion logic, signup branching, gift properties, and sale-week edits are the long work. Budget two to four weeks for four journeys with DNS and forms. Never cut over during your highest-LTV catalog week.
        </p>
        <p>
          Match team shape to tool temperament. Solo founders bias toward time-to-live; retention operators bias toward holdout tests and browse depth. Agencies help either stack, but hours are a line item. See <a class="link" href="/guides/implementation-plan">implementation plan</a> for sequencing.
        </p>
        <h2>Five-job buyer test with scoring rubric</h2>
        <p>
          Score zero to two on: welcome by signup source; abandoned checkout with inventory check; post-purchase excluding gifts; replenishment with subscription suppression; winback split by discount sensitivity. Zero equals CSV exports. Two equals native edit before a drop. Paper-test both tools — demos lie.
        </p>
        <p>
          Time-to-live beats theoretical max when no retention engineer exists. A tea shop may accept ninety percent of maximum if ninety percent ships in one afternoon. A keyboard shop may need browse depth enough to wait two weeks for setup.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing scenario: 15,000 contacts, selective lifecycle sending</h2>
        <p>
          Picture 15,000 contacts, 1,400–2,200 orders monthly, 32,000–48,000 marketing emails in a normal month, higher in November and May. Profile billing charges for the full pool even when only engaged segments receive lifecycle mail. Send-weighted billing charges every broadcast you panic-send during a heatwave SKU miss.
        </p>
        <p>
          Holdout tests change ROI math. If winback discounts move customers who would reorder anyway, platform fees are not the expensive line — mis-measured incrementality is.
        </p>
        <h2>Migration sequencing and collision guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Export consent timestamps and suppressions. Rebuild welcome and cart first; parallel-monitor two weeks. Predictive segments, CRM pipelines, and push automations need explicit replacements — document what you are giving up. Pause legacy flows before enabling new ones.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hybrid stacks without priority docs duplicate cart recovery. If capture lives elsewhere, tag handoff must be explicit. See <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">flow collision prevention</a> before running two senders through sale week.
        </p>
        <h2>Measurement guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Separate replenishment from winback attribution. Tea and coffee merchants over-credit discount winback for natural consumption cycles. Hold out five percent of new subscribers on welcome tests. Measure incremental GMV with holdouts, not default dashboards.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multichannel requires one trigger-ownership spreadsheet reviewed before big sends. Tools do not replace ops discipline; some make violations easier to catch in preview.
        </p>
        <h2>Hybrid stack patterns on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Common pattern: capture in Privy or Justuno, lifecycle in Omnisend, SMS in Postscript when compliance matters. Failure mode: three cart recovery senders with no priority order. Pick a primary lifecycle owner.
        </p>
        <p>
          Camping quiz capture fed education sequences while flash SMS handled weekend promos — with forty-five-minute suppression between cart channels. Collisions dropped before volume rose.
        </p>
        <h2>Who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Omnisend if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>You need cart, welcome, and post-purchase live in days</li>
          <li>You will use prebuilt multichannel journeys with email, SMS, and push weekly</li>
          <li>Contacts plus message volume fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Omnisend without external rescue</li>
          <li>Switching cost favors Omnisend for the next twelve months</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Yotpo Email & SMS if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack</li>
          <li>You will use reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite weekly</li>
          <li>Modular plans by product fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Yotpo Email & SMS without external rescue</li>
          <li>Incremental lifecycle GMV justifies Yotpo Email & SMS migration</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Omnisend is the better Shopify email tool when you need cart, welcome, and post-purchase live in days. Yotpo Email & SMS is the better Shopify email tool when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Run the five-job buyer test in both UIs, model twelve-month billing with real sends and list hygiene, and pick whichever platform lets you edit audiences safely the Thursday before a drop — not whichever sales deck had the prettier logos. See <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">selection framework</a> and <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">pricing models</a> before annual contracts.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/yotpo-email-sms-vs-omnisend">Yotpo vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-yotpo-email-sms">Klaviyo vs Yotpo</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-omnisend">Sequenzy vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/reviews-and-ugc">Reviews and UGC</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">Selection framework</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Omnisend vs Yotpo Email & SMS FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
